title: Economic Sustainability
author: Saurabh Agrawal
text:
We live in a connected planet. Whether a facebook post of an uprising in a closed society spreads like fire or a man made war provides ample reason for financial markets to wildly swing, our society has become more global and interconnected. Although our future is still largely governed by our direct actions but other events outside of our control are increasingly contributing to our destiny as well.

Sustainable Development Goals is an initiative which attempts to study the present world we live in and try to provide a framework through which humanity can have a responsible and improved life i.e. a sensible, prosperous and fair society which lives in harmony with its environment.

There are three primary goals which SDG proposes to meet.

First, an economic development where countries and societies have access to minimum acceptable resources which are required for a decent human life.
Second, an inclusive social culture which promotes equality amongst its citizens and its ability to distribute resources amongst its citizens and lastly a society whose actions help our planet live in more peace with the environment.

Economic development promotes a more self sufficient, prosperous culture. The advancements in technology making our productions systems more efficient have to be developed keeping environmental safety in mind. The clean energy over other sorts of means have to be preferred. Increased productivity, either society as a whole or an individual person, is also a measure of economic development.

Social development would mean inclusion of every segment of the society. A rich country does not necessarily mean a good thing if majority of the wealth is concentrated within small section of the population. Social inclusion calls for spread of wealth and other resources amongst all the population. No discrimination on the basis of color, region, sex etc should be allowed to restrict even distribution of resources within the society.

Environment is changing around us. Inspite of advancements in technology, fresh water is many regions of the world is still an unmet goal. Directly impacting the environment since industrial revolution, we are changing the pace of pollution, both as safety hazard in the air as well as in the seas.

Our solution has to come from both good intent as well as necessity.
Our intent should be to make our planet a more happy place, where we are able to provide every world citizen access to basic human needs.
Necessity is due to realization that our 24/7 connected world doesn’t discriminate when it comes to unwanted consequences because of somebody’s else actions. A terrorist threat can suffocate your everyday life. As an another example, a country’s manufacturing practices could increase world pollution.

So we need to address the situation from both the fronts i.e. bridge the gap between rich and poor:
First we need to create mechanisms for richer and more capable societies to share their wealth and their technical know how with the rest of the world in exchange of assurances that a more able and stable ‘rest of the world’ would mean less interruptions to their own progress.

Secondly, we need to empower the poor sections of our society via education and other common sense tactics so that they become a better contributor to the society and thus in turn less dependent on aid and other favors.

Both of these methods will enable a better level playing field for all of humanity and thus gives us more natural start of equality amongst all.
